AB  - Nowadays mobile devices are more robust and portable with a wide range of helpful functionalities to help individuals accomplish daily life. Due to the advancements in mobile technologies, the issue of mobile learning has been extensively examined in electronic learning research. Numerous researchers agree that it is crucial to use the pedagogical and technical advantages of mobile technology in learning environments. In this rapidly changing world, students are being exhorted more and more to use their mobile phones exclusively for educational purposes. Mobile phones, alongside a multitude of feature-rich applications, enable students to study from home and conveniently access all the necessary learning resources with just a single click, allowing them to invest their time in understanding. Mobile applications are used for the online education system to continue studies. For exploring mobile applications in an educational environment, a new tool is presented known as the probabilistic linguistic T-spherical fuzzy set (PLT-SFS), providing a more robust approach to handling uncertainty in complex judgment scenarios. Within a PLT-SF framework, the construction of a hybrid decision model that combines weighted aggregated sum product assessment (WASPAS) with integrated determination of objective criteria weights (IDOCRIW) is the objective of the proposed study. Following that, a real-life scenario is presented to assess the efficacy of the proposed technique in determining the most effective mobile application for learning. In this study, a comprehensive analysis was conducted on popular educational mobile applications, including Google Classroom, Kahoot, Photomath, Toca Life World, Coursera, Brainly, and Duolingo, to evaluate their effectiveness in enhancing educational efficiency through novel proposed methodology. © 2026 Elsevier Ltd.
